1a

Marginal Models for correlated outcomes. since in Hw5, it is a conditional model.

If it is a conditional model, one should use a GLMM model. So it is not suitable for

fitting a marginal model via GEE. Also if the dataset becomes larger, will fit more

GEE requirement that dataset be large.

1b

compared the two formula of Naïve or ‘model-based’ variance of β estimator and

Robust or ‘Empirical’ (Sandwich) variance of β estimato in slides 13, it implies

two foumulas will get the same output by the conoutation of matrix.

1c

Advantages of implementing a GEE model over a GLMM model:

1.Marginal’: for longitudinal data, mean response is conditional only on covariates at that time and NOT on other responses or covariates at other time points and NOT on random effects.

2.Marginal models do not require the joint distributional assumptions for the vector of responses

  1. Marginal models SEPARATELY model the mean response and the covariance (within-subject or within-cluster association) among repeated responses (1,2,3 from slides)

4.The point estimates, on the other hand, are the same as with the models for independent data. Sandwich variance estimation, which sandwiches the expected (A matrix or bread) and observed (B matrix or meat) information to produce robust error estimation, is also used. Even for independent data, the sandwich is a powerful estimator, producing heteroscedasticity consistent standard error estimates.

Equation for this marginal model:

Logit(pr(yij=1/pr(yij=0 )))

=beta1+beta2racew + beta3 month + beta4 * monthsquared +beta5* noshow + beta6*discussion +

beta7* socsup +beta8racew:month + beta9racew:monthsquared+ beta10month:noshow +beta11monthsquared:noshow+ + beta12month:discussion+ beta13monthsquared:discussion + beta14month:socsup +beta15monthsquared:socsup

####2b

Important assumption in a marginal model: g(μij)=g{E(Yij|Xij)}

Independent Yi AND no assumed distributional assumption, the independence assumption for R.

For longitudinal data, mean response is conditional only on covariates at that time and NOT

on other responses or covariates at other time points and NOT on random effects.

Working Covariance matrix of Yi conditional on Xi is Vi = Ai1/2 Ri Ai1/2

#####2c

Canonical Link function for mean response, μij: g(μij) = log(μij/(1-μij)

2d(i)

H0: beta_racew:month= beta_racew:monthsquared = 0

Ha: at least one of them not 0

conclusion and interpretation:

Since the effect size is 489 is not large enough, even the p=0.053

quite small, but we still cannot reject null hypothesis directly.

Might need more test to make sure.

                 id=id, corstr = "ar1", std.err="san.se")

zcor.toep[,2]<-apply(zcor[,c(2,5)],1,sum)

We can see the within-subject association alphas are 0.409, 0.306, 0.251.

logOR(Yij, Yik) = α = 0.409, 0.306, 0.251.

OR(Yij, Yik) = exp(alpha) = exp(0.409, 0.306, 0.251.)

so for month time baseline, the OR of the month=0 and month=6,12,24 are exp(0.409) so for month time month=6, the OR of the month=6 and month=0,12,24 are exp(0.306) so for month time month=12, the OR of the month=6 and month=0,6,24 are exp(0.251)
